<div id="review_650891096" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/650891096" />
    <a title="Malia" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5953660-malia"><img alt="Malia" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1610664683p2/5953660.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/650891096?book_show_action=true">Jun 25, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Malia" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Malia" href="/user/show/5953660-malia">Malia</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5953660-malia?shelf=mystery-suspense">mystery-suspense</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer650891096" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6918934747957472382">This is the first book by this author that I have read, although she has come up as a recommendation for a while. My resistance must have been intuition, because this book was not quite for me. That is not to say it is a bad book, not at all, it just felt quite long and dragged out at parts, as well as the solution feeling too sudden and almost simplistic. (I won&apos;t give away anything, but anyone who has read this might know what I mean when I say that Toni&apos;s revelation in the end felt almost ant</span>
  <span id="freeText6918934747957472382" style="display:none">This is the first book by this author that I have read, although she has come up as a recommendation for a while. My resistance must have been intuition, because this book was not quite for me. That is not to say it is a bad book, not at all, it just felt quite long and dragged out at parts, as well as the solution feeling too sudden and almost simplistic. (I won't give away anything, but anyone who has read this might know what I mean when I say that Toni's revelation in the end felt almost anti-climactic, because it seemed so obvious throughout the book, I assumed it was a given?!?)<br />Anyway, the ending aside, the story was quite gripping, as stories about missing children so often are. They are scary and awful and you think immediately of their vulnerability and fear. Gudenkauf really does show the parent's emotional states in a believable, terrifying manner, especially Martin's (one of the fathers). The chapters alternate between character's voices, a tool I generally enjoy, but which somehow felt a bit annoying here. I was slightly confused about jumps in time, and it took me a while to adjust to the structure of the story.<br />While I did not particularly warm to any of the characters (one of the reasons the many POVs didn't work for me), I had sympathy for their situations. Gudenkauf is a talented writer and I don't want to disparage her style just because this particular book only earned three stars in my opinion. She crafted a logical story, and writes elegantly, even when writing in different voices. <br />I feel as though I'm not being very articulate in this review, maybe it's because there's something a bit puzzling and a little unsatisfying about this book. But now that I think about it, maybe that was Gudenkauf's intention, to leave us feeling a bit weird about the whole thing.<br /><br />Find more reviews and bookish fun at <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="http://www.princessandpen.com">http://www.princessandpen.com</a></span>
  <a data-text-id="6918934747957472382" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

